	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I have no idea about that engineering equitation, but try even reading through the first nerdy nights. That's not even SNES. Games have a ridiculous amount of programming, which is huge amounts of math. I enjoy it somewhat, but it gets old. And when you have so much data you have to manipulate, it becomes truthfully, a nightmare.
<br />
<br />And as for assembling them? A run of 100 games with all needing rewiring even for one chip would be stupid hard. First 5 may be fun, but 100 can only be fun for so long.
<br />
<br />And why be so nice when the scammers are not? I mean, I'd help if I could, but SNES isn't a homebrew-crazy platform like NES because it's complex and most of the only reason is to make pirates/bootlegs/whatever you call them. I mean, I don't think that's a bad thing myself, I look at the knowledge and know how should be available and everyone should be able to do it, but the fact is that we can't stratle the line of legality, because one day if it's passed, this site will be no more and all valuable knowledge that wasn't preserved will pretty much be lost. It's not worth helping 1 person out to their contention. I'd help if I knew, but I don't. I mean, I'm sure you can find Mask ROM pinouts for SNES and maybe some other chips like the MAD-1 online and then you shouldn't have to do anything more. Use that as a starting block. I hope you know how computers work, as this isn't something you can do in one week of study unless you have a good background in it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


