	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If you want a cartridge for a specific game, buy the real deal</div><br />How so for "games that haven't been released in America" such as fan translations?<br /><br />OK, new tack without the piracy overtone: How does one build Lock-On style devices that perform the equivalent of IPS patches, into which one plugs "the real deal"? Codemasters did it for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_Genie#SNES" class="postlink">Game Genie</a>, and Sega did it for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_%26_Knuckles#Lock-on_technology" class="postlink">Sonic &amp; Knuckles</a>.</div>
<br />
<br />I missed this earlier. Such a device would be neat but I'm not sure how practical it is. Given that translations patch an enormous amount of data or even expand the ROM you would need a device with alot of memory with ICs that could quickly figure out if any accessed ROM address is needing to be intercepted. 
<br />
<br />Infact you'd probably be better off with something more like a cartridge emulator (like a backup device) or with operation tuned to this application.
<br />
<br />Instead of loading a ROM from a Disk or SD card, it would read the ROM of the inserted cartridge. Then you could have it read from media (CF, SD, whatever) for patch data. But with patch data you could basically patch anything into whatever game, making it a Flash Cart/Cartridge Emulator anyway.
<br />
<br />It is a neat idea but it just isn't practical.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


