	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've already made a sound engine for the SNES which works under real hardware but I lost the sources, I can still share my copiled SPC and a disassembled source but it wouldn't be of many uses.
<br />However, I'd be ready to re-do it any time it's really not complicated. It's basically the same as the NES but with more features, and the most complicated thing is to prevent the "note on click" that happen if you key on on a channel which was already playing, a pop happens. So your engine should be careful to always key off at least one frame before you key on.
<br />
<br />Other than that, anyone who made a NES sound engine should be able to do a SNES one.
<br />
<br />Also the problem for me is not making the engine but making the editor for the PC. If people are ok with me releasing a SPC engine that requires you to type .dbs in a text file then I can release one anytime.
<br />Or maybe a MIDI-&gt;ASM converter that makes assemblable files of lots of .db out of a MIDI file.
<br />
<br />The problem with this is that SPC limitations have nothing to do with MIDI limtations (same with XA) so converting is not very optimal.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
